Subject:Re: [Antenna-discussion] Photon orbital momentum free
	spacecommunication.
Levente,

Bo Thide did not invent the notion of quantized orbital angular momentum, 
and the infinite range of possibilities thereof.

This was done in 1913 by Niels Bohr.

Your are correct that this notion is worthy of a Nobel prize -- which was 
awarded to Bohr in 1922.

-------------
Thide is a latecomer to this game, who makes dramatic claims that well-known 
physics could revolutionize the communications industry.

But, as you note, it is technically awkward to use the high orbital angular 
momentum states of light.

People are working hard on this, and no doubt some measure of success will 
be achieved in implementing this 100-year-old idea.

My personal take is that a "revolution" is unlikely.

It is generally much easier just to increase the frequency of the lowest 
angular-momentum mode used in, say, fiberoptics, to increase the number of 
bits/sec that can be transmitted.   Next, it's easy to bundle multiple 
fibers into a cable to increase further the bit-transmission rate per cable.

Nonetheless, we technogeeks are optimistic that some niche can be found for 
the use of higher orbital angular momentum modes.   So far, we are still 
waiting....

--Kirk



