Subject: [Antenna-discussion] Photon orbital momentum free 
spacecommunication.


  Hallo.

  This is an update, and a pickup on a debate in Antennex on the
matter, that stalled in a draw, as I recall, a year ago.

  About a year ago there was a proposition and crude demonstration
by Bo Thide of the Swedish Institute of Space Physics in Venice Italy,
claiming that selecting different orbital momentums for photons, an
infinity of communication channels can be opened up on the same
single frequency channel.
  That would be earthshaking, worthy of a quick Nobel Prize, if true.

  A year ago I took a close look at the Venice experimental setup,
and was underwhelmed. It was a reflector antenna, reflector slit
and twisted into a corkscrew, the split separated axially by one
wavelength(?).
  To me - at least - that was a geometric arrangement, that distorted
the aiming point of the antenna into a cone, where every part of the
cone carried the same info + a fixed phase shift of the carrier.
No orbital momentum visible to this engineer.
  Prof Bo Thide had a different assessment, obviously.

  Now the matter is revived, and still contested:

http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-20217938

There are plenty of links for details, arguments, conterarguments.

I like the Laszlo B. Kish / Robert D Nevels paper

http://vixra.org/pdf/1209.0107v7.pdf

for its brevity, arguing, that many orbital modes in free space
would violate fundamental rules of particle physics and the
Second Law of Thermodynamics.

  It would be nice, if somebody commenting, would remember
the name of the old thread from a year ago.

best regards
Levente
AC2EK






